  <section class="section prose-section">
    <div class="prose-intro">
      <p class="eyebrow">About Pagani North</p>
      <h2>Music about what survives beneath responsibility.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="prose-body">
      <p>Pagani North makes intimate songs about memory, responsibility, longing, and the parts of ourselves we sometimes have to leave behind.</p>
      <p>These are not songs about escaping responsibility. They are about the emotional cost of carrying it: the versions of ourselves that become difficult to remember, the futures we stop imagining, and the moments that unexpectedly restore what we believed was gone.</p>
      <p>The music lives in quiet rooms—acoustic instruments, worn textures, restrained arrangements, and lyrics that treat memory not as decoration, but as something alive enough to wound and heal.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section manifesto">
    <p class="eyebrow">The Ghost of the Boy</p>
    <h2>Some lives are not lost.<br />They are buried so another life can continue.</h2>
    <p>Sometimes we have to put away the life that might have been in order to be present for the life that depends on us. There is a price for that. The title track lives in the moment when someone comes along and brings that forgotten part of you back into the light.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="behind-the-song" class="section prose-section artifact-story">
    <div class="prose-intro">
      <p class="eyebrow">Behind the title track</p>
      <h2>The song moves from survival to resurrection.</h2>
      <a class="button button-outline" href="/assets/the-ghost-of-the-boy-handwritten-chords.pdf" target="_blank">Open the chords</a>
    </div>
    <div class="prose-body">
      <p>The title track is about the cost of becoming who life required you to be, and what happens when someone awakens the person you once had to forget.</p>
      <p>The boy was not forgotten by accident. Remembering him—and the life that could have been—would have made the life of duty and responsibility impossible to sustain. The line “I buried him before he buried me” captures that deliberate act of emotional survival.</p>
      <p>The bridge changes the song. She wakes the boy “without a séance,” bringing back what had been treated as dead. The final verses do not offer a simple escape from the present. They show the buried life returning through dreams, memory, and the fragile belief that the years spent running could never fully remove the boy.</p>
      <p>The chords are shared for anyone who wants to play the song.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
